Mystery solved: That's why we can't tickle ourselves
A kind of brake in the cerebrum prevents people from tickling themselves. Scientists at Humboldt University in Berlin found this with the help of experiments on rats, as they reported on Thursday evening. Progress has also been made on the question of why children are so fiercely resisting tickling, only to then demand more.
Finally, it has also been shown why it is only the approximation of a tickling hand that triggers laughter even before touching. This is due to a deep layer in the cerebellum that triggers laughter even when the tickling is expected.
According to reports, previous research showed that rats react with "laughs" in the ultrasound area when tickled by humans. This "laugh" is mediated by the part of the cerebral cortex, which serves as the central processing of haptic perception.
Laughter is suppressed during self-contact
So far it has been assumed that the brain can distinguish between self-touching and touching by others - that is why humans cannot tickle themselves. However, in the experiments on the rats, the Berlin researchers have now found that laughter as well as the activity of the relevant area of the cerebral cortex are suppressed during self-touching. This is also the case if the living beings in the tickle themselves and in the tickle themselves.
However, if self-touching and touching by others at the same time, laughter is also suppressed. This suggests that the rat’s brain cannot distinguish between self-touching and touching by others. The new findings suggested that humans cannot tickle themselves because self-touching activates a brake in the cerebellum.
The rats were also trained to tickle themselves. In doing so, they sometimes stopped this initiation in the experiment prematurely, exhibiting flight behavior or scare stiffness. This ambivalence is similar to the behavior of the children. The ambivalence of tickling is a behavioral reaction that is the same in rats and humans.
