Attention: Smartphone NEVER charge wirelessly
Practical but harmful
Although inductive technology via Qi standard is extremely practical, it should still not be used.
Since several new smartphones have come on the market, which support wireless charging and sell very well - especially the new iPhone 11 models, we would like to recall again a study from the beginning of July. While wireless charging mobile devices is extremely convenient, it is not necessarily recommended.
Higher temperature increases battery
Researchers warn against wireless charging of smartphones. According to the findings of the University of Warwick, this is extremely harmful for the devices. The reason for this is the significantly greater heat development. If you charge a mobile phone normally via cable, the battery heats up to 27 degrees in three hours. When charging wirelessly, the power rises even slightly higher with the perfect alignment of the smartphone on the charging pad, the battery always rises in excess of 30 degrees.
Capacity and lifetime
According to the researchers, the temperature is a decisive factor for the durability of batteries. Every single degree plays a role. When charging at higher temperatures, the battery does not only change in capacity, but it does not last as long as it does. So the lifetime is shorter. The researchers therefore advise to always charge the smartphone by cable. Since a battery replacement with modern smartphones is always associated with a high cost, this should be a helpful tip.
Practical
The technology is extremely convenient: Simply place the device on a corresponding charging pad - these are now even installed in many restaurants, airports, hotels and cars - and the battery is charged without annoying cable salad and tedious plug fummelei. Since Qi (stands for inductive power transmission) is only a worldwide standard, in which, exceptionally, even Apple should participate in the technology, there are hardly any restrictions.
